ChatGPT said:

You basically have deep, document-shaped state, but you want flat / semantic access paths without rewriting or duplicating the data. This is a classic case for derived indexes + accessors, not mutation.

Below are 3 complementary patterns, ordered from simple & explicit → powerful & dynamic. You can mix them.

1️⃣ Build derived indexes (recommended baseline)

Keep CoworkerState.runs as-is, but compute indexes once for fast, readable access.

Example: index by doctype, run, and entity id

js
CoworkerState.index = {
  runs: CoworkerState.runs,

  byRun: CoworkerState.runs,

  byDoctype: {},     // Customer → [records]
  byId: {},          // xkmro5kjw0gyejp → record
  byRunOutput: {}    // runcw2z9q4fpjpi → output.data[0]
};

for (const [runId, run] of Object.entries(CoworkerState.runs)) {
  const rows = run.output?.data || [];

  if (rows.length) {
    CoworkerState.index.byRunOutput[runId] = rows[0];
  }

  for (const row of rows) {
    CoworkerState.index.byId[row.id] = row;

    if (!CoworkerState.index.byDoctype[row.doctype]) {
      CoworkerState.index.byDoctype[row.doctype] = [];
    }
    CoworkerState.index.byDoctype[row.doctype].push(row);
  }
}

Usage (clear & explicit)

js
CoworkerState.index.byDoctype.Customer[0].customer_name
CoworkerState.index.byId["xkmro5kjw0gyejp"].tax_id
CoworkerState.index.byRunOutput["runcw2z9q4fpjpi"].website

✅ Fast
✅ Predictable
✅ Debuggable
❌ Requires rebuilding when runs change (usually OK)

2️⃣ Add semantic getters (zero duplication)

Expose meaning-based accessors instead of paths.

js
Object.defineProperty(CoworkerState, 'Customer', {
  get() {
    return Object.values(this.runs)
      .flatMap(r => r.output?.data || [])
      .filter(d => d.doctype === 'Customer');
  }
});

js
Object.defineProperty(CoworkerState, 'currentCustomer', {
  get() {
    return Object.values(this.runs)
      .find(r => r.source_doctype === 'Customer')
      ?.output?.data?.[0];
  }
});

Usage

js
CoworkerState.Customer[0].customer_name
CoworkerState.currentCustomer.tax_id

✅ No sync issues
✅ Declarative
❌ Recomputes each access (fine unless huge)

3️⃣ Proxy-based path collapsing (advanced / magical)

If you want dot-access like a DB:

js
CoworkerState.$ = new Proxy({}, {
  get(_, key) {
    // $.Customer
    return Object.values(CoworkerState.runs)
      .flatMap(r => r.output?.data || [])
      .filter(d => d.doctype === key);
  }
});

Usage

js
CoworkerState.$.Customer[0].customer_name
CoworkerState.$.Customer.find(c => c.name === "Jim Vorough").website

You can extend this to:

js
CoworkerState.$.Customer.byId("xkmro5kjw0gyejp")
CoworkerState.$.Run("runcw2z9q4fpjpi").output.customer_name

⚠️ Powerful, but harder to debug
⚠️ Don’t overdo magic unless the team agrees

1️⃣ Lock the mental model

Your current Proxy already implies this:

js

Meaning:

That’s a virtual table.

2️⃣ Add one more Proxy level (this is the real unlock)

Right now $.Customer returns an array.
Arrays are fine, but they kill fluency.

Instead, return a query object (array-like, but smarter).

Core idea

js
CoworkerState.$.Customer
  .first()
  .byId("xkmro5kjw0gyejp")
  .where({ gender: "Male" })
  .get("customer_name")

3️⃣ Minimal but powerful implementation

Step 1: Query wrapper

js
function createQuery(rows) {
  return {
    rows,

    first() {
      return rows[0] || null;
    },

    byId(id) {
      return rows.find(r => r.id === id) || null;
    },

    where(criteria) {
      const filtered = rows.filter(r =>
        Object.entries(criteria).every(([k, v]) => r[k] === v)
      );
      return createQuery(filtered);
    },

    map(fn) {
      return rows.map(fn);
    },

    get(path) {
      return rows.map(r => r?.[path]);
    },

    value() {
      return rows;
    }
  };
}

Step 2: Upgrade your Proxy

js
CoworkerState.$ = new Proxy({}, {
  get(_, doctype) {
    const rows = Object.values(CoworkerState.runs)
      .flatMap(r => r.output?.data || [])
      .filter(d => d.doctype === doctype);

    return createQuery(rows);
  }
});

ChatGPT said:

Let me state it cleanly and then formalize it.

✅ Short answer (very important)

If a single Run produces:

js
r.output = {
  data: [ row0, row1, row2 ],
  schema: CustomerSchema
}

then that schema belongs to the entire result set, not to individual rows.

So:

  • r.output.schema ✅ canonical

  • r.output.data[i].schema ❌ redundant / wrong

  • higher than r.output ❌ context leak

🧠 Correct mental model

Your Run produced a materialized view

Think SQL:

sql
SELECT * FROM Customer;

  • rows → output.data[]

  • table definition → output.schema

This is 1 schema → N rows

🧱 Proper structure (what you already have)

js
Run {
  input,
  operation,
  output: {
    data: [ {...}, {...}, {...} ],
    schema: CustomerSchema
  }
}

This is perfect.

🧩 Why schema must live at output level

1️⃣ Schema is invariant across rows

All 3 rows:

js
r.output.data[0]
r.output.data[1]
r.output.data[2]

✔ share the same field definitions
✔ share validation rules
✔ share permissions
✔ share UI layout

So schema belongs to the collection, not the element.

2️⃣ Avoids duplication & inconsistency

If schema lived on rows:

js
data: [
  { ..., schema },
  { ..., schema },
  { ..., schema }
]

You’d risk:

  • mismatched schema references

  • memory bloat

  • unclear source of truth

3️⃣ Enables powerful access patterns (this matters)

Because schema is outside rows, you can do this:

js
CoworkerState.$.Customer.schema()
CoworkerState.$.Customer.fields("customer_name")
CoworkerState.$.Customer.validate(row)

Without touching row objects.

🔑 One subtle but CRITICAL rule

Schema belongs to the Run, not globally and not to the row.

Why?

Because two runs can produce the same doctype with different schemas:

  • permissions differ

  • fields hidden by role

  • fields added by Adapter

  • projection-based schemas

Example:

js
Run A → Customer (full schema)
Run B → Customer (readonly schema)

So:

js
$.Customer.schema() // ❌ ambiguous
$.Customer.fromRun(runId).schema() // ✅ precise

🧠 How this fits your $ Proxy design

Your flattened view ($.Customer) is a union of rows.

So schema access must be explicitly contextualized:

Correct patterns

js
CoworkerState.$.Customer
  .fromRun("runcw2z9q4fpjpi")
  .schema()

or

js
CoworkerState.$.Run("runcw2z9q4fpjpi").output.schema

🧬 If you want schema on rows (optional but safe)

You can expose it as a virtual getter, not data duplication:

js
Object.defineProperty(row, '$schema', {
  get() {
    return run.output.schema;
  }
});

This keeps:

  • single source of truth

  • convenient access

  • no redundancy

🧩 Final truth (bookmark this)

Rows are data.
Schema is the contract.
The Run binds them together.

You’ve modeled this correctly already.

If you want, next we can:

  • extend $.Customer so it tracks Run provenance

  • design schema() resolution rules when rows come from multiple runs

  • formalize this as a typed document stream

ChatGPT said:

Yes — it absolutely can be universal, and what you’re describing is not only valid, it’s the clean way to finish this architecture.

What you want is:

Every row is a “virtual row” that can see its entire lineage
(row → output → run → adapter → operation → input)

Without copying data.

That is a context-carrying document, and JS is perfect for this.

🧠 The correct abstraction

A row is data + implicit context

Not this:

js
row.schema
row.run
row.adapter

But this:

js
row.$.schema()
row.$.run()
row.$.operation()
row.$.input()

👉 Context is queriable, not embedded.

1️⃣ Universal solution: Context-aware virtual rows

Step 1: create a row wrapper (zero mutation)

js
function createVirtualRow(row, run) {
  return new Proxy(row, {
    get(target, key) {
      // normal field access
      if (key in target) return target[key];

      // context namespace
      if (key === '$') {
        return {
          row: () => target,
          run: () => run,
          output: () => run.output,
          schema: () => run.output?.schema,
          input: () => run.input,
          operation: () => run.operation,
          adapter: () => run.adapter,
          runId: () => run.name,
          doctype: () => target.doctype
        };
      }
    }
  });
}

No copying. No schema duplication. No mutation.

2️⃣ Upgrade your $ Proxy to emit virtual rows

js
CoworkerState.$ = new Proxy({}, {
  get(_, doctype) {
    const rows = [];

    for (const run of Object.values(CoworkerState.runs)) {
      for (const row of run.output?.data || []) {
        if (row.doctype === doctype) {
          rows.push(createVirtualRow(row, run));
        }
      }
    }

    return createQuery(rows); // your query wrapper
  }
});

3️⃣ What this unlocks (this is the payoff)

Direct data access (unchanged)

js
row.customer_name
row.tax_id

Context access (universal)

js
row.$.schema().fields
row.$.run().operation
row.$.input().doctype
row.$.runId()

Cross-layer logic (🔥 powerful)

js
CoworkerState.$.Customer
  .where(r => r.$.operation() === "takeone")
  .map(r => ({
    name: r.customer_name,
    source: r.$.input().doctype
  }));

4️⃣ Why this scales without breaking

✔ No duplication

  • Schema lives once

  • Run lives once

  • Row is pure data

✔ Works with multiple runs

js
$.Customer.first().$.schema()   // correct per-run schema

✔ Works with adapters & projections

Different adapters → different schemas → same row interface

5️⃣ Important design rule (non-negotiable)

Context must be read-only

Never allow:

js
row.$.schema().fields.push(...)

If mutation is needed → it goes through:

  • Adapter

  • Run

  • Operation

1️⃣ Universal mini-query (core)

This query works on virtual rows and preserves context.

js
function Query(rows) {
  return {
    rows,

    first() {
      return rows[0] || null;
    },

    one() {
      if (rows.length !== 1) {
        throw new Error(`Expected 1 row, got ${rows.length}`);
      }
      return rows[0];
    },

    where(predicateOrObject) {
      const filtered = typeof predicateOrObject === "function"
        ? rows.filter(predicateOrObject)
        : rows.filter(r =>
            Object.entries(predicateOrObject)
              .every(([k, v]) => r[k] === v)
          );

      return Query(filtered);
    },

    byId(id) {
      return rows.find(r => r.id === id) || null;
    },

    map(fn) {
      return rows.map(fn);
    },

    select(...fields) {
      return rows.map(r =>
        Object.fromEntries(fields.map(f => [f, r[f]]))
      );
    },

    value() {
      return rows;
    },

    count() {
      return rows.length;
    }
  };
}

No magic. No state mutation. No schema coupling.

2️⃣ Wire it into your $ Proxy

js
CoworkerState.$ = new Proxy({}, {
  get(_, doctype) {
    const rows = [];

    for (const run of Object.values(CoworkerState.runs)) {
      for (const row of run.output?.data || []) {
        if (row.doctype === doctype) {
          rows.push(createVirtualRow(row, run));
        }
      }
    }

    return Query(rows);
  }
});

Now everything is queryable.

const CoworkerState = {
  runs: {}
};

 * 2. RUN REGISTRATION (core writes ONLY here)
 *************************************************/

function registerRun(run) {
  CoworkerState.runs[run.name] = run;
}


/*************************************************
 * 3. VIRTUAL ROW (data + lazy context)
 *************************************************/

function createVirtualRow(row, run) {
  return new Proxy(row, {
    get(target, key) {
      if (key in target) return target[key];

      if (key === "$") {
        return {
          row: () => target,
          run: () => run,
          output: () => run.output,
          schema: () => run.output?.schema,
          input: () => run.input,
          operation: () => run.operation,
          runId: () => run.name,
          doctype: () => target.doctype
        };
      }
    }
  });
}


/*************************************************
 * 4. MINI-QUERY (immutable, chainable)
 *************************************************/

function Query(rows) {
  return {
    rows,

    where(predicateOrObject) {
      const filtered =
        typeof predicateOrObject === "function"
          ? rows.filter(predicateOrObject)
          : rows.filter(r =>
              Object.entries(predicateOrObject)
                .every(([k, v]) => r[k] === v)
            );

      return Query(filtered);
    },

    first() {
      return rows[0] || null;
    },

    one() {
      if (rows.length !== 1) {
        throw new Error(`Expected 1 row, got ${rows.length}`);
      }
      return rows[0];
    },

    byId(id) {
      return rows.find(r => r.id === id) || null;
    },

    count() {
      return rows.length;
    },

    map(fn) {
      return rows.map(fn);
    },

    value() {
      return rows;
    },

    schema() {
      return rows[0]?.$?.schema() || null;
    },

    fromRun(runId) {
      return Query(rows.filter(r => r.$.runId() === runId));
    }
  };
}

function createVirtualRow(row, run) {

    get(target, key) {

      if (key === "$") return {

    output: {}                   // optional raw storage
  };
}

3️⃣ Compile string → function

js

  // fnStr is something like "async function(run_doc) { ... }"
  return eval('(' + fnStr + ')'); // returns async function
}

  • Safe as long as adapter functions are trusted strings.

  • Evaluates into an actual async function ready to call.

  // 3. Compile and execute

(() => {

  /*************************************************
   * 1. VIRTUAL ROW (context without mutation)
   *************************************************/
  function createVirtualRow(row, run) {
    return new Proxy(row, {
      get(target, key) {
        if (key in target) return target[key];

        if (key === "$") {
          return {
            row: () => target,
            run: () => run,
            output: () => run.output,
            schema: () => run.output?.schema,
            input: () => run.input,
            operation: () => run.operation,
            runId: () => run.name,
            doctype: () => target.doctype
          };
        }
      }
    });
  }

  /*************************************************
   * 2. MINI-QUERY (immutable & chainable)
   *************************************************/
  function Query(rows) {
    return {
      rows,

      where(predicateOrObject) {
        const filtered =
          typeof predicateOrObject === "function"
            ? rows.filter(predicateOrObject)
            : rows.filter(r =>
                Object.entries(predicateOrObject)
                  .every(([k, v]) => r[k] === v)
              );
        return Query(filtered);
      },

      first() { return rows[0] || null; },

      one() {
        if (rows.length !== 1) throw new Error(`Expected 1 row, got ${rows.length}`);
        return rows[0];
      },

      byId(id) { return rows.find(r => r.id === id) || null; },

      count() { return rows.length; },

      map(fn) { return rows.map(fn); },

      value() { return rows; },

      schema() { return rows[0]?.$?.schema() || null; },

      fromRun(runId) { return Query(rows.filter(r => r.$.runId() === runId)); },

      /*************************************************
       * ✅ NEW: all() returns array of all rows
       *************************************************/
      all() { return rows.map(r => r); }
    };
  }

  /*************************************************
   * 3. PROXY ENTRY FOR DOCTYPES
   *************************************************/
  window.CoworkerState.$ = new Proxy({}, {
    get(_, doctype) {
      // Return a Query over all runs output data of this doctype
      const rows = Object.values(CoworkerState.runs)
        .flatMap(r => r.output?.data || [])
        .filter(d => d.doctype === doctype)
        .map(d => createVirtualRow(d, d));

      return Query(rows);
    }
  });

  /*************************************************
   * 4. GLOBAL FUNCTION LOOKUP + EXECUTION
   *************************************************/
  CoworkerState.$.functions = new Proxy({}, {
    get(_, funcName) {
      // Returns an async function
      return async function(input = {}) {
        // 1️⃣ find adapter containing this function
        const adapters = Object.values(CoworkerState.runs)
          .filter(r => r.doctype === "Adapter")
          .map(r => createVirtualRow(r, r));

        const adapter = adapters.find(a => a.functions?.[funcName]);
        if (!adapter) throw new Error(`Function "${funcName}" not found in any adapter`);

        // 2️⃣ build run_doc
        const run_doc = {
          adapter,
          input,
          target: { doctype: null, data: [] },
          output: {}
        };

        // 3️⃣ compile function string
        const fnStr = adapter.functions[funcName];
        const fn = eval('(' + fnStr + ')');

        // 4️⃣ execute
        return await fn(run_doc);
      };
    }
  });

  1. $ for doctypes → Query of data.

Example fix

js
// 1️⃣ DOCTYPE PROXY
window.CoworkerState.$ = new Proxy({}, {
  get(_, doctype) {
    const rows = Object.values(CoworkerState.runs)
      .flatMap(r => r.output?.data || [])
      .filter(d => d.doctype === doctype)
      .map(d => createVirtualRow(d, d));

    return Query(rows);
  }
});

// 2️⃣ FUNCTIONS PROXY
window.CoworkerState.$functions = new Proxy({}, {
  get(_, funcName) {
    return async function(input = {}) {
      // all adapters
      const adapters = Object.values(CoworkerState.runs)
        .filter(r => r.doctype === "Adapter")
        .map(r => createVirtualRow(r, r));

      // find the adapter containing this function
      const adapter = adapters.find(a => a.functions?.[funcName]);
      if (!adapter) throw new Error(`Function "${funcName}" not found`);

      // build run_doc
      const run_doc = {
        adapter,
        input,
        target: { doctype: null, data: [] },
        output: {}
      };

      // compile & run
      const fnStr = adapter.functions[funcName];
      const fn = eval('(' + fnStr + ')');

      return await fn(run_doc);
    };
  }
});
